<font color="#FF0000">GERALD</font><br>
<tt>Tue Mar  4  7:23:06 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The Soviet Union never used the American Communist Party for espionage. The reason, obviously, is because all members of the American Communist Party were watched like a hawk by the FBI. The Soviets were afraid that Oppenheimer might join the American Communist Party, or at least talk to members, and they warned him repeatedly to stay away from those people. If strange men watched your home, they were bad people because they watched your home, not because they called themselves &quot;Communists&quot;. I agree with you when you say &quot;There is a world of difference in labeling innocent people 'Communist' and recognizing that there were some real and dangerous ones out there.&quot; That's precisely the point. It's not the label &quot;Communist&quot; that determines whether someone is evil. It is what they do. The men responsible for ordering tanks into Hungary in 1956 were evil because they did that. Those responsible for massacres in Indonesia and Nigeria were also evil even though they were not Communists. When Kruschev pounded his shoe on the table in the United Nations, and said &quot;We will bury you&quot;, he meant &quot;We will bury you economically.&quot; What he meant was that the Soviet Union would be so economically successful and prosperous, they would be universally wealthy, while the American capitalist system would collapse into universal poverty. As rediculous as that sounds today, that's what he meant.<br><br>
It's not a game to me. It wasn't a game to the two million Vietnamese killed by Americans. There's a big difference between satellites which are in space, which doesn't belong to anyone, and planes which invade another country's air space, which does belong to them. I doubt you would be so forgiving if Soviet planes flew over Alaska. <br><br>
I never said that everything done by the American government is wrong. I did say that not everything done by the American government is right, which is a sentiment often expressed here, and is the sort of belief that got us into Vietnam. The American government did not get invloved in Vietnam out of altruistic compassion to help the poor South Vietnamese.<br>
The actions of some Communists do not justify what our government did in Chile and El Salvador. We have to recognize what our government has done, and what their motivations are, so this can not happen again. One of the lessons of Vietnam is to not accept our leader's word at face value. 
